BEAUTIFUL NOISE
A stage musical inspired by the music of Neil Diamond
Written by Paul Waldren
BEAUTIFUL NOISE is set in Manhattan NY in 1967. The hippy movement is in full swing,
civil rights are front and centre and Elvis and the Beatles have changed music forever. It has
also created a generational gap, more a chasm, between the older conservative generation
and their children who are embracing the new age of rock n roll.
Beautiful Noise is a story that tells the journey of a young 17 years old boy on the verge of
opera/classical music greatness. It celebrates music for what it is – the most emotive and
natural form of communication in the world. BEAUTIFUL NOISE, at its core, is a story that
embraces the big band music of the time and rock n roll and meshes them together in a story
that celebrates the music of Neil Diamond.
Beautiful Noise will demonstrate that the gap between all forms of music is really a
subjective divide. One that should be transcended by our appreciation of the creativity in
many forms of music. This stage show will showcase the big bands – not hide them under the
stage. They are an integral part of the show, as are the audience.
The SET: The set for BEAUTIFUL NOISE is designed to highlight and contrast the opera
versus rock dynamic. Stage left, we have our orchestra. The orchestra is on a turntable stage
and can enter and exit the set as required. Depending on stage limitations, some may by in
the pit. Contrasting this, we have a rock and roll band (guitar, drums, trumpet, keyboard) on
a turntable stage right. Both stages can be on set simultaneously, or individually. Back of
stage we have a choir to be used in support and for harmonies and is only visible when lit.
Our action takes place centre stage with a limited number of simple sets being bumped in and
out under darkness between scenes. Most sets will consist of one key backdrop, lighting
changes and some prop replacements.

SCENE 1 : THE CONFLICT (SET IN INTERIOR, FAMILY ROOM IN A NEW YORK
APARTMENT)
In this scene we open the show on Stage left. We see and hear a young man singing La
donna e mobile from Verdi’s Rigoletto as he wraps up rehearsal. It is an opportunity
for our audience to see the orchestra on stage. As the song completes, lights drop.
Centre stage is lit, and we see a mother and father discussing the upcoming
performance of their son Joel at a concert at New York’s Lincoln Centre in the staging
of Puccini’s Turandot. Some of America’s leading operatic artists will be performing
before Lance Markhoff, director of music at the Denmark School and famous
composer, as well as New York’s leading Classical Music promoter Janelle Jonas. Many
are performing, but Markhoff and Jonas are there to see this young prodigy first hand.
Play La Boheme
Joel enters having come from rehearsal.
DAD (Ben Cohen)
This is his big chance. Janelle tells me that Leonard Bernstein himself is attending.
MOM (Elena Cohen)
How exciting for Joel
JOEL (son)
What’s exciting?
MOM
Your father says Mr Bernstein is coming Wednesday night.
DAD
Let’s hope he is not busy with his Black Panthers. So, tell me, how did you do today?
JOEL
It was ok. Too much Verdi
MOM
Just OK darling?
DAD
Too much Verdi?? Impossible! There is never too much Verdi. Ah,that would be right. Why
excel when you can be just OK? Why won’t you commit yourself? Such talent and so wasted
on you. If I had …….
JOEL( cuts him off…)
Well dad, I guess we will never know will we. And for all the accolades you placed on that
Pavarotti guy who just performed in la Boheme at the NY opera, it would seem that you may
be the only person who has ever heard of him, and probably ever will. Maybe you should
consider the fact that there is now an Elvis album in over half of Americas homes. I’m not
even sure Pavarotti even has an album, does he? Did it ever occur to you that I, and most
others might prefer Elvis over Opera?
DAD
Argh. Such misery. You mark my words son, we will all be listening to Mr Luciano Pavarotti
long after the world has forgotten Elvis “the hips” (wiggling his hips) Presley. What do they
teach you at that school? Why are they not teaching you about Pavarotti in music class? It’s
not just me, Mr Bernstein has also acclaimed him.
JOEL
At least Leonard Bernstein recognises great music when he hears it, regardless of any so-
called style or genre or who is performing it. And so far as school goes, if they made us all
sing opera, I’d be the only one in class. I enjoy singing other songs. Enough of the classical
already! Maybe I’ll send my songs I’ve written to Leonard Bernstein….
DAD
What songs? Enough???. Already….???
MOM
Stop it you two. Sit and eat. Now! Joel, so tell me, how was rehearsal really? It’s a very big
night for you tomorrow.
JOEL
It was ok (dad interrupts)
DAD
There it is again. Just ok? Do you understand the opportunity you have been given? Ah, if I
had only the same opportunity. I would have cherished it. I would not sing this rubbish from
the radio. I would sing for HaShem (how Jewish people refer to God). You would see. But the
Nazis took that, just like they took everything else from us. And now you. This. You do the
same...
JOEL
Here we go1. Anyway, I’m not even sure I want to be a singer. No one at school wants
anything to do with me. I think I might be a songwriter. I might write songs for Elvis, or The
Beatles? I think I enjoy composing and writing more than singing anyway. I’m sorry mum,
I’m not hungry. I’ll be in my room. (Joel departs)
MOM
(Facing her husband, hand on hips) See what you’ve done now! You just won’t leave it alone
will you. Oh, and I also like Elvis. And I like The Beatles. And you know what Ben, I really
enjoy that Satisfaction song by the Rolling Stone. (hums “I cant get none, no no no…)
DAD
Don’t you dare woman. Do not speak those words in my presence. The Rolling Stones are
more vulgar and less talented than even Elvis – and mark my words that is saying something.
None of these fly-by-night popular music groups will last. Especially not the Rolling Stones.
Can you imagine anyone wanting to listen to their music in 50 years? Hey? No, of course
not!
Anyway – what songs is he talking about that he has written? He should only be practicing
his singing!
MOM
We will see Benjamin, we will see.
(and leaves the room)
Ben is left standing forlorn and places an album (La Scala) on the record player. We
hear the first few bars from opening scene of Turandot. (Orchestra Stage Left) - Set
darkens.
SCENE 2 : THE PERFORMANCE (SET AS STAGE OF THEATRE)
Scene opens with applause as Joel enters for his final scene of Turandot. Joel performs
Nessun Dorma (live orchestra stage left) to rapturous applause. His parent’s pride is
matched only by the enthusiastic disbelief of the two opera big wigs at the talent
demonstrated by this young, dark handsome boy/man of New York City. Following the
performance, we are taken back stage as Joel’s parents accept the accolades on his
behalf. Joel notices a girl from school – Caroline – an awkward greeting follows.
Play Nessun Dorma
JANELLE JONAS (with Markhoff and Joel, his parents)
Well that was a huge success. I am already getting requests for further performances.
LANCE MARKHOFF
Congratulations Joel, your performance tonight is the talk of the season. The world appears
to be your oyster.
JOEL (distracted)
Ar, thanks, I guess. Yes, thank you. Can you all excuse me for a moment….
JOEL (approaching a young lady that has caught his attention)
Hi, I know you from school, right?
CAROLINE
Hi Joel, Um, I’m here with my parents. They’re big fans. Actually, so am I. Of the
performance I mean. Not you. But you too. You were wonderful. Oh, I’m sorry, you don’t
even know who I am do you?
JOEL
(Interrupting, laughing). Thanks. I think. I know who you are. Caroline, right? I hear you’re
about to join our music class, a year ahead of your classmates – you must be very good for
Spriggs to allow that!
CAROLINE
Oh, I don’t know about that. I play the piano and keyboard and Mr Spriggs needs that I
believe. I sometimes play with my dad’s band. It’s just a bit of fun really. You know – “rock n
roll and stuff (as she completes an awkward little wiggle)
JOEL
Your dad plays rock n roll? Really? Wow! Maybe I can come and see you play sometime –
seems only fair.
CAROLINE
(Being called away by her parents) Sure. I’ll let you know. See you at school. Bye.
SCENE 3 – THE ATTRACTION (SET IN SCHOOL MUSIC CLASS)
In this scene we see Joel, the morning after the concert, being teased by classmates while
waiting for music class to commence.
STUDENT 1
So opera boy, how did it go? While you were singing that old fogey stuff, we were all
jamming. We’re going to be the American Beatles.
Joel ignores the jibes, he’s used to it. Unexpectedly, Caroline jumps to his defence
CAROLINE
I don’t think so boys. You’ll still be dribbling over your silly girly magazines watching Joel
on TV. He’s going to be a star.
Much whooping and surprise. Joel doesn’t know how to respond so just smiles at
Caroline as the music teacher enters class.
TEACHER (Mr Spriggs)
OK team assume your positions. Joel, nice work last night. I hear Carnegie Hall is next.
Good luck. As for the rest of you, you know this week we’re up paying tribute to my dear
friend Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart and in particular the andante from the second movement of
his Concerto 21. Joel, I believe you and the band have had some success last week in
modernising this timeless piece into something our class may enjoy?
(Teacher looks over at band). As you all know, we have lost our keyboard to a school on the
west coast., Caroline would you mind?
JOEL
Yeah, sure. I think we have captured the essence of the piece. I mean the lyrics are still a
work in progress, but we think we have the melody.
This link demonstrates the inspiration behind Song Sung Blue
MR SPRIGGS
As you all know, we have lost our keyboard to a school on the west coast., Caroline would
you mind?
CAROLINE
Oh, well I’m not sure Mr Spriggs, I haven’t had a chance…..
MR SPRIGGS
You’ll be fine. Just place yourself close to Joel and he will help you through it.
The audience can feel the tension of the attraction between Caroline and Joel as she
squeezes past Joel to her position on Keyboard.
Song Sung Blue (inspired by Mozart Concerto 21) is performed by small school band stage
right with Joel on guitar and Caroline sheepishly on keyboard. (Orchestra joins).
(Company chorus supports the performance as classmates).
Play Song Sung Blue
SCENE 4 : THE BEGINNING – (SET IN JOEL’S PARENTS KITCHEN)
Joel is off stage. Mum and dad again listening to classical music on the radio. The phone
rings. Mum answers and somewhat surprisingly announces it’s for Joel.
MOM
Someone called Caroline from school.
The conversation is one that Joel handles very awkwardly, especially when he grasps
the thrust of it. The audience can see Caroline lit off stage on the phone. She is
explaining to Joel that the band she plays in with her dad has lost its singer and they
have a big gig this coming weekend.
CAROLINE
Hi Joel, it’s Caroline here from music class. Hi. Yeah, hi. So, here’s the thing, Mikey, the

Saturday night at the 44
th
St Club? I know you would be great.
JOEL
Ohhh, yeah I guess so Caroline. Math hey. Yeah, it’s hard. I’d be happy to help if I can. Just

MOM
(Feeling quite pleased) Yes, that’s fine, but don’t be late. You have much to practice for
Carnegie Hall, and your own study.
JOEL
Caroline? Yeah hi. Yeah, that’s fine. I’ll see you for math study tomorrow.
CAROLINE
(Confused) ahhh, OK, great, Thanks Joel. See you then (Caroline looks surprised, shrugs and
hangs up).
(Dad enters scene)
MOM
Joel has a date.
JOEL
It’s not a date!
DAD
A date? With whom
JOEL
It’s not a date!
MOM
With the pretty girl we saw at the Lincoln Center who plays the piano.
JOEL
It’s not a date!
DAD
He doesn’t have time for dates..
JOEL
It’s not a date!
DAD
I cannot comprehend this. (to Elena) How can you allow it?
JOEL
(With less conviction) It’s not a date!
MOM
It’s a simple date. Don’t make a fuss Ben.
JOEL
(Exhausted) It’s not a date!
DAD
A simple date? He has a date already. It’s with Carnegie Hall. I will forbid it.
JOEL
(Now almost inaudible) It’s not a date.
MOM
(Firm but quietly direct stare at Ben). It’s a simple date. He promises to be home early and

DAD
OK. Just this one date. That is all. One date.

(exasperated) It. Is. Not. A. Date.
SCENE 5 – THE CONSPIRACY – (Set in Caroline’s garage).
Scene opens with Caroline’s dad’s band singing I’m a Believer by The Monkees ( a hit
written by Neil Diamond). As song ends, we see Caroline and Joel enter.
MACK
OK guys, lets get this right. I’m a believer, I really am.
Play I’m a Believer
CAROLINE
I know you can do this Joel. You can sing anything better than anyone I’ve ever heard.
JOEL
Oh, I don’t know. I mean – with Carnegie Hall and all, I really can’t do this Caroline. I’ve
been writing though. I have a few songs I can ask your dad to look at. I think they would
work for the band.
CAROLINE
That’s great. We can do that. But right now we need a guitar who sings. You’re here aren’t
you. Why did you come? Because you want to do this. I tell you what – jam with us now and if
you don’t want to come to 44
th
Street on Saturday night we will find someone else OK?
JOEL
OK – just for practice – nothing more.
CAROLINE
In her excitement leans forward and pecks Joel on the cheek. Joel’s reaction is one of
amazement. It’s a small gesture by Caroline but a pivotal moment for Joel.
OK dad, we’re ready. Let’s do this.
Caroline introduces a still dazed Joel to the band – her dad Mack and the others. Once
Joel has met everyone, Mack takes charge.
MACK
Alright Joel, welcome to Mack and the Pack.. Let’s start with a song I wrote for my wife,
Cherry – or am writing, I guess. We will kick it off and you just join in when it feels right. The
lyrics are on top there.
The band strikes up a pretty ordinary version of what is called “Song for Cherry”, (in
fact it sounds a bit too much like Sherry by the Four Seasons) which Joel sings – poorly.
He can’t quite get the rhythm of the song and all present are starting to think they’ve
made a mistake.
MACK
Joel, are you sure you can do this (looking concerned at Caroline)
JOEL
(Still somewhat clumsily staring at Caroline)
Um, ah, well I think so Mack. It’s just that the chords are all a bit jumbled, and the lyrics
don’t seem to fit the rhythm of the music. Would you mind if we just changed it a little?
MACK
Change it a little!! Why would you want to fix what isn’t broke?
CAROLINE
Daaaadd…just let him have a go. Go ahead Joel.
Joel smiles at Caroline and picks up a guitar, strumming some chords and humming.
JOEL
See, I think it really only needs 3 chords. Keep it simple. A bit like this…..
Joel plays the revised (familiar tune of Cherry Cherry) as the others (eventually
including a reluctant Mack) gather round him. The audience are left with the group
collaborating over the new improved version - Cherry Cherry. We get a taste of what
we’ll hear at the gig on Sat night.
SCENE 6 – THE BEAUTIFUL NOISE – (Set in Joel’s bedroom)
Joel is strumming his guitar and humming a tune. He can’t recall ever feeling this
happy. His mum enters carrying a basket of clean washing.
MOM (as she puts away Joel’s clothes)
That doesn’t sound like singing practice. How did your study go?
JOEL
Huh? Oh, It’s not mum. It’s so much better than just singing – it’s creating. There is no end
to the music we can create. Listen mum – there’s music everywhere. Yes, classical, but also
pop, rock, folk, country – it’s everywhere and I love it all.
MOM
And the studying with Caroline?
JOEL
Oh that? That was OK? Oh, and I’m going back over on Saturday night – not a date mom! –
to help her some more.
MOM
Really? Just OK hey? Not a date hey? OK, whatever you say darling. But I must say, I do
think it was maybe a bit more than OK? I remember when every noise I heard sounded
beautiful and romantic. Some call it being in love.
JOEL
Mommmm, don’t be stupid. This has got nothing to do with Caroline. It’s the music, can’t
you hear it? It’s what I want to do mom. It’s my destiny…
MOM
Hear what? All I hear is those cabs and the sounds of what I call the New York City band. As
for your destiny, well I think we will all learn your destiny at Carnegie Hall. (Mum leaves
the room).
We hear the continued noises coming up through Joel’s window (horns, sirens, cars etc.
Joel is in love and it’s making everything around him sound especially sweet. We enter
a fantasy scene with the Orchestra Stage left supporting Joel as he sings Beautiful Noise.
Joel is supported by Mom and the ensemble who are characters on the street. All get
songlines in this performance of Beautiful Noise
Play Beautiful Noise

SCENE 8 – THE FIGHT – (Set in Cohen Family Room)
In this pivotal scene, the crux of the plot is exposed – that all music has some quality to
it, that the beauty of the art of music, like all the arts, is its subjectivity.
Elena has Barbie from across the street over when Ben arrives home. Joel arrives soon
after and is introduced.
MOM
Hello honey. Joel, this is Barbie from across the street, you know Barbie.
BARBIE (friend of Elena)
Oh, this young man needs no introduction, I’ve heard him sing.
Joel’s parents are surprised, as they didn’t have their neighbor pegged as an opera buff.
They realize their instincts were right when she corrects their assumption by saying she
saw Joel on Sat night at the 44
th
Street Club.
BARBIE
Elena, you told me Joel was practicing singing, but I had no idea how good he was. Have you
been to the Club and heard him? Everyone loved him. We were all dancing and drinking –
maybe a bit too much of both to be honest……
MOM (trying to save the situation)
Oh no Elena, you must be mistaken – it was probably Joel’s friend Alex – they look so alike –
they are mistaken all the time. Anyway – its time I got dinner on, thanks for dropping by…
BARBIE
No. It was him. This boy is a star, and so handsome. He is UNMISTAKABLE! I tell you….
Barbie is cut off by Ben (Dad) as Ben slams the table with his fist.
DAD (to Barbie)
Enough! Get out, get out now.
Elena ushers a deeply worried and afraid Barbie from the house and then returns
looking equally worried and too afraid to speak. Eventually Ben says something.
DAD
Is that woman right?. Did you go to the Club and sing in some polluting rock n roll band?
You told us you were studying. You will never see that girl again. I told you Elena, she cannot
be trusted.
JOEL
Yes, I did. I did it to help Caroline’s dad on Saturday night. And I will see Caroline again, I
assure you. She is the only real friend I have ever had.
MOM
Just once Ben, no real harm done. You hear – only once, not again….
JOEL
Well actually, I’m not sure that will be true mom. I loved it. I love singing and I love
composing. I just love music. Why must it be one or the other? Why can I not love singing
opera and also love singing songs I know I can write.
DAD
(Now furious) I will not allow you to again take this from me. I forbid it. Is it not enough that
Hitler took your grandparents, your cousins, my brother and my singing? He took my
singing! I will not let you also take it from me.
JOEL
Enough with the Nazi’s already! I didn’t stop you from singing dad. Hitler didn’t stop you.
No. You did that. Stop trying to blame me for your fears and failures. It’s not my
responsibility to sing for you. I am grateful to you and mum for everything you’ve given me,
but I do not owe you my voice. Why won’t you sing now dad, hey, why? Who is stopping
you? Not me, not mum, not Adolf Hitler! Why won’t you sing? Are you still afraid? Of what?
C’mon lets sing now (Joel somewhat belligerently starts singing an opera – more yelling it
than singing)
MOM (now very upset and crying)
Stop it. Stop it both of you. I will not allow song to come between this family.
DAD
If that boy continues to defy me. If he refuses to stop seeing that girl, IF, he intends to again
pollute the gift HaShem has given him, he is not part of this family – he is no son of mine.
Should he not be grateful for this gift. Should he not be dedicating his voice to HaShem, at
the Synagogue or at the Opera? It is this yetzer hara (* an inclination to pursue evil in
Judaism) to be tolerated? I think not.
Listen to me son. You have a choice to make. You either commit to not ever sing with that girl
again, and promise to dedicate yourself to real, pure music, or you can leave. But hear this,
as it is my solemn pledge. Should you choose to betray me, you will have no place at our
table. You are not my son.
Ben exits leaving Joel and his mother.
MOM
(calls after her husband) You cannot say that. Do not ever say that (the door slams)
He does not mean that Joel. He loves you, you see he says bad things when he is hurting. The
pain, it never leaves him.
JOEL
I know mom. But he can’t control my life like this. He is killing my love of music, just as the
Nazi’s killed his. It is not me, or my choice of which song I sing that makes him angry, you
know that. Why does he hate modern music? All music has its place and is a creation to be
appreciated. Why do we have to love opera but not jazz – that’s crazy. I think your friend
Barbie enjoyed my singing on Saturday night as much as anyone did my performance last
week at the Lincoln Center. And you know what, I enjoyed it too. Does this mean I no longer
love opera – no it doesn’t. But it does mean there is more to my life than JUST opera.
(Joel stands to leave the conversation)
And if dad doesn’t like it, then he will lose his son! He doesn’t even know me. He was never
around. He is only ever there when I sing his bloody opera. He loves opera, not me!
MOM
But Joel….(it’s too late, Joel walks out of the room. The set darkens as we hear Elena
quietly sobbing) Oh Shilo, where are you now
SCENE 9 – THE DECISION – (set in Music Class)
We see only Caroline and Joel in the room. Caroline is facing Joel holding his hands
CAROLINE
You have to make up with him Joel. He’s your father. Your poor mother. Will they come and
see you on Saturday Night at the club.
JOEL
No way! You don’t understand Caroline, there is no point. He refuses to even let me come

What if, what if. What if you have nowhere to live? We need to get you somewhere to live. We

Mack and your mom are so cool. And Mack agreeing to play my songs. I mean, wow.
CAROLINE
Yeah, they’re ok I guess. I’m just glad we have somewhere for you to stay. I’m even more
glad that it’s close to me. But you’ve got it wrong with dad. He’s not doing you a favour. He

JOEL
I’ve never had a friend like you Caroline.
CAROLINE (sheepishly)
Oh sure you have. You must have had loads of friends.
JOEL
Nah, not really. Just Shilo. But you know, he wasn’t even real.
CAROLINE
What do you mean, he wasn’t real?
JOEL
This is embarrassing, I don’t even know why I’m telling you. You’ll think I’m weird.
CAROLINE
No, I won’t, promise. Who was, is Shilo?
JOEL
You’ll need to sit down for this. Joel answers in song with Shilo

SCENE 12 – THE PLOT THICKENS – (Set in the Bungalow, Janelle visiting Joel,
Caroline also there)

JANELLE

JANELLE

INTERMISSION
PART TWO
The second part of the show essentially provides the platform for a performance of
many of Neil Diamond’s greatest hits. The mood of the show notably shifts from angst
and a conservative setting, to an upbeat, hit driven performance that involves the
crowd. One innovation to facilitate this is via a screen above the stage (previously un-
noticed that will provide the words to some songs performed by the cast and encourage
audience participation).
The show moves from Joel’s fractured relationship with his father to his developing love
for Caroline, but most importantly, his arrival as a singing sensation – albeit not in
opera, but in popular music, and a whole lot more……
In embracing his new self, Joel becomes so focused on his chance at stardom, he is
prepared to sacrifice not only his relationship with his father, but also that with
Caroline.

Taking his bows for his final performance of the evening, we see the back of Joel. He is

Lighting is key in this event – creating the emotion and recognition that all performers
are collaborating.
Live audience will respond, Joel takes his bows, acknowledges the musicians, kisses and
waves to the audience and rushes off stage as lights drop. We are again back stage.

ANNOUNCER
Now many of you have seen our next guest perform here previously. He was a child prodigy
and is now simply prodigious. He has recently completed a sell-out US tour and returns to

Joel enters the stage to rapturous applause.
